I'm almost certain this is probably wrong, I'm just getting back into c++, but the iterator class needed a postfix increment in order for this simple example to compile:

```cpp
py::iterator iter2iter(py::iterator s) {
    return py::make_iterator(std::begin(s), std::end(s));
}
```

Usage of `operator&` for custom smart pointers leads to unexpected behavior. In my case segmentation fault occurs when i trying to run code:

```
// C++ code

template<class T>
class my_custom_ptr
{
    // ...
    T** operator*() { /* return address of internal pointer */ }
    // ...
};

my_custom_ptr<some_object> get_object()
{
    return my_custom_ptr<some_object>( new some_object );
}

PYBIND11_MODULE(module, m)
{
    m.def( "get_object", &get_object )
    py::class_<some_object, my_custom_ptr<some_object>>( m, "some_object" );
}

// Python code
import module
obj = module.get_object()
```

